[StudyName "Pawn Structures"]
[ChapterName "Ari Ziegler - Mikael Johansson Åstorp 1990"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/lb9E9CZa/CoIVU0Hs"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Elyson"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.24"]
[UTCTime "07:47:36"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 { This is a common variation of the King's
Indian Defence. The centre is closed so play
is shifted to the flanks.
Black's pieces are placed to act on the kingside. The key move is ... f5 followed by ... f4 and then the g-pawn
will advance to open up files towards White's
king. White wants to make his key move, c5, and penetrate on c-File with the major pieces. } 9... Nd7 10. Nd3 { [%cal Gc4c5] } 10... f5 { [%cal Gf7f5] } 11. Bd2 c5 { A radical way to prevent White's key
move, but White now has a new way to break
up Black's pawn-structure, with the advance
b4. More common than the move played is
11 ... Nf6 12 f3 Kh8 with the idea ... Neg8
and .... Bh6. } (11... Nf6 12. f3 Kh8) 12. Rb1 Nf6 13. f3 f4 { [%cal Gg2g4] } 14. g4!? { This move looks crazy at first, as you sel-
dom want to advance the pawns in front of
your own king. However, in the race to
break through first, White wants to create a blockade on the kingside. The move g4 is
similar to Black's ... c5, directed against the
opponent's natural key move. } { [%cal Gc3c5,Gb3b5,Ga2a5] } 14... h5 (14... fxg3 { [%cal Gf4g3] } 15. hxg3 { [%cal Gf1f2,Gf2h2] }) 15. h3 Kh8 { Black has problems in organizing his pieces.
The purpose of Kh8 is to free the g8 square for N on e7
then Nh7 to cleaar out the dark squares for queen and bishop } { [%cal Gg8h8] } 16. Be1 { [%cal Ge1h4] } 16... Nh7 17. Rf2 Ng8 { [%cal Gd8h4] } 18. Rg2 { It is instructive to see how calmly White
plays. Before his own breakthrough, he sup-
presses Black's counterplay. Closed positions
are seldom as sensitive to tempi as open
ones; instead it is the placing of the pieces
that is important. } 18... Bf6 (18... Ng5 19. Rh2 { [%csl Gh3,Gg5] }) 19. b4 { [%csl Gc5,Gd6,Ge5] } 19... b6 (19... cxb4 20. Nb5 a5 21. a3 bxa3 { [%csl Ga5] } 22. c5 { [%cal Gc4c5] }) 20. bxc5 bxc5 (20... dxc5 21. a4 { [%cal Ga4a5] } 21... a5 { [%csl Rb6] }) 21. Qa4 a5 22. Nb5 { [%csl Gb5,Gd6] } 22... Ra6 23. Qa3 { White knows the basic rule that an attack
on a flank is best answered by a counterattack
in the centre. Therefore he prepares a knight
sacrifice on d6 or c5. If the two pawns disap-
pear, the black spine will disappear. White
gets two dangerous passed pawns, but also
the possibility of winning the e5-pawn. This
will allow an attack on the a1-h8 diagonal. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gg6g4] } 23... Bh4 24. Bc3 Ng5 { [%cal Gh7g5] } 25. Nxd6 Nxh3+ 26. Kf1 Rxd6 27. Qxc5 Bg3 (27... hxg4 28. Nxe5 Kh7 29. Nxg4) (27... Bf6 28. gxh5 gxh5 29. Nxe5) 28. Nxe5 Kh7 29. Qa7+ Kh6 30. Rb8 { [%cal Gc4c5] } 30... Qe8 31. c5 Qa4 { [%cal Gc5c8,Gd5d7,Ge4e6] } 32. Rxg3 Ba6 33. g5+ Nxg5 34. Ng4+ hxg4 35. Qg7+ Kh5 36. Qh8+ Nh6 37. fxg4+ Kh4 38. Qxh6+ Kxg3 39. Be1# *


